# lib/vk/vk_2d.ad
#
# Hamnix native 2D primitive layer for the Vulkan-shaped spine.
# GPU track #181 — Phase A of unifying the desktop environment (DE) and
# the hamSDL game layer onto ONE vk backend.
#
# ===================================================================
# WHY THIS EXISTS
# ===================================================================
# lib/vk/vk_core.ad + lib/vk/vk_raster.ad give a depth-buffered 3D
# TRIANGLE pipeline. But the two things we actually want to accelerate
# with a future GPU — the DE compositor (lib/hamui_host.ad + kernel
# devwsys) and hamSDL (lib/hamsdl.ad) — draw 2D primitives: solid
# rects, alpha-blended overlays, image/sprite/glyph blits, and lines.
# Today each of those has its OWN private software rasterizer, so vk is
# an island. This file adds the 2D vocabulary to vk so that, in Phase B
# (hamSDL) and Phase C (DE), those callers can route their primitives
# THROUGH vk unchanged in behaviour — and a later GPU backend behind the
# same vk API then accelerates the whole desktop + every game for free.
#
# ===================================================================
# DESIGN CHOICE: dedicated 2D fast-paths (NOT the triangle rasterizer)
# ===================================================================
# A rect could be two triangles and a blit a textured quad on the
# existing barycentric rasterizer. We deliberately do NOT do that here:
#   * The triangle rasterizer writes interpolated color with an OPAQUE
#     store — it has no source-over alpha blend. The DE scrim/overlay
#     (e.g. the #00000066 screenshot dim) and hamSDL both REQUIRE
#     source-over blending; expressing it on the 3D path would mean
#     adding a blend stage there anyway.
#   * DE/hamSDL primitives are axis-aligned integer rects, nearest-
#     neighbour scaled RGBA blits, and Bresenham lines — direct pixel
#     writes are both simpler and BIT-EXACT to the code they replace,
#     which is what lets Phases B/C be behaviour-preserving (and lets
#     this file's host test assert unforgeable golden pixels).
# These ops write the SAME color-image backing store the 3D render pass
# and the present path use (VkImage.mem_base, row-major RGBA8888), so
# they COMPOSE with vkCmdDraw in one command buffer and present through
# the unchanged vkQueuePresent / vk_present_to_window path. They are NOT
# a side channel: vk_core records them as VK_OP_2D_* command-buffer ops
# replayed against the bound render-pass color image at vkQueueSubmit.
#
# ===================================================================
# ALPHA / BLEND CONVENTION (must match the code Phases B/C replace)
# ===================================================================
# Source-over, identical integer formula to hamui_host _put_px_blend and
# the device compositor _wsys_cache_putpixel:
#     out_channel = (src*a + dst*(255 - a)) / 255
# The vk color target is treated as an OPAQUE compositing surface (it is
# what gets presented to the screen): any touched pixel with a>0 leaves
# dst alpha = 255; a==0 leaves the destination byte-for-byte untouched;
# a==255 is a plain opaque store. RGB channels are R,G,B in bytes 0,1,2
# and alpha in byte 3, matching VK_FORMAT_R8G8B8A8_UNORM.
#
# All colors are packed 0xRRGGBBAA (R in the high byte), exactly like
# vk_raster_clear's clear_rgba, so 0x101828FF reads as #101828 opaque.
#
# ===================================================================
# ADDER NOTES
# ===================================================================
#   * No function-local nested Arrays: all storage is the caller's
#     kmalloc'd image backing, reached through raw base pointers, just
#     like vk_raster.ad.
#   * Pure integer math — the rendered image is bit-deterministic so the
#     host self-test can checksum / sample exact pixels.
#   * EXTERN-FREE and target-agnostic (like lib/hamsdl.ad's core): it
#     compiles for BOTH x86_64-bare-metal (the kernel vk spine) and
#     x86_64-linux (the QEMU-free host render-to-PPM self-test).


# --- low-level pixel writers into an RGBA8888 color image -----------
#
# color_base: host pointer to the image's row-major RGBA8888 backing.
# img_w/img_h: image dimensions in pixels (the clip rectangle).
#
# PERFORMANCE NOTE (GPU track #181, CPU-path optimization):
# The primitives below HOIST clipping to the whole primitive: each
# fill/blit/mask/roundrect clamps its rectangle to the image bounds ONCE
# up front, so the inner pixel loop runs with NO per-pixel bounds branch.
# Opaque writes go through a single packed-RGBA `uint32` store instead of
# four byte stores. Output is BYTE-IDENTICAL to the per-pixel clipped path
# (the color target is little-endian RGBA8888: a packed word
# r | g<<8 | b<<16 | 0xFF<<24 lays the same bytes r,g,b,255 in memory as
# the four byte writes it replaces). `_vk2d_store` / `_vk2d_blend` remain
# for the (small) line brush and as the reference clipped primitives.

# --- BGRA store-order (Phase D.3: BGRA-native GPU present) ----------
#
# The default color target is little-endian RGBA8888 (bytes r,g,b,a) — the
# SW /dev/fb present path and every existing caller depend on that byte
# layout, so it stays the DEFAULT and is byte-for-byte unchanged.
#
# The native virtio-gpu scanout backing, however, is BGRA8888 (the byte
# order QEMU's VIRTIO_GPU_FORMAT_B8G8R8A8_UNORM host resource wants). When
# a caller renders a frame it will present through the GPU device, it can
# ask vk2d to lay pixels down in BGRA byte order instead — then the present
# is a pure device DMA (TRANSFER_TO_HOST + FLUSH) with NO RGBA->BGRA
# convert copy (Phase D.2 measured that convert eating the whole 61x win).
#
# The mechanism is a single module-level store-order flag. When set, every
# vk2d primitive swaps the R and B channels of its source color BEFORE the
# (unchanged) store code runs, so byte0 receives B and byte2 receives R —
# i.e. the exact same code path deposits BGRA bytes. A source-image blit
# additionally swaps the sampled source R/B (the source stays RGBA; only
# the destination byte order flips). The blend math is per-channel and
# symmetric, so a translucent BGRA store composites over a BGRA destination
# identically to the RGBA case. Result: a BGRA-rendered frame is
# pixel-identical in VISIBLE color to the RGBA render — only the in-memory
# channel order differs. Default (flag == 0) leaves the RGBA path intact.
_vk2d_bgra: int32 = 0


def vk2d_set_bgra(on: int32):
    # Select the store byte order for subsequent vk2d primitives:
    # 0 = RGBA8888 (default, byte-unchanged), non-0 = BGRA8888 (GPU scanout).
    if on != 0:
        _vk2d_bgra = 1
    else:
        _vk2d_bgra = 0


def vk2d_get_bgra() -> int32:
    return _vk2d_bgra


def _vk2d_pack_opaque(r: uint8, g: uint8, b: uint8) -> uint32:
    # Packed little-endian RGBA8888 word with alpha forced opaque (0xFF):
    # in memory this is bytes [r, g, b, 255] — identical to four byte
    # stores of r,g,b,255 on the LE color target.
    return cast[uint32](r) | (cast[uint32](g) << 8) \
           | (cast[uint32](b) << 16) | (cast[uint32](255) << 24)


def _vk2d_store(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64, img_h: uint64,
                x: int64, y: int64,
                r: uint8, g: uint8, b: uint8, a: uint8):
    # Opaque store of one pixel, clipped to the image bounds.
    if x < 0 or y < 0:
        return
    if x >= cast[int64](img_w) or y >= cast[int64](img_h):
        return
    o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](y) * img_w + cast[uint64](x)) * 4
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0] = r
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0] = g
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0] = b
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 3)[0] = a


def _vk2d_blend_at(o: uint64, r: uint8, g: uint8, b: uint8, a: uint8):
    # Source-over blend of one RGBA pixel at an ALREADY-CLIPPED byte offset
    # `o` into the color image. Same integer formula as _vk2d_blend, but
    # with the bounds check hoisted out to the caller's clamped loop.
    # out = (src*a + dst*(255-a)) / 255 ; a==0 no-op ; a==255 opaque.
    if a == 0:
        return
    if a >= 255:
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0] = r
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0] = g
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0] = b
        cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 3)[0] = 255
        return
    av: uint32 = cast[uint32](a)
    ia: uint32 = 255 - av
    dr: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0])
    dg: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0])
    db: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0])
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0] = cast[uint8]((cast[uint32](r) * av + dr * ia) / 255)
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0] = cast[uint8]((cast[uint32](g) * av + dg * ia) / 255)
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0] = cast[uint8]((cast[uint32](b) * av + db * ia) / 255)
    cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 3)[0] = 255


def _vk2d_blend(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64, img_h: uint64,
                x: int64, y: int64,
                r: uint8, g: uint8, b: uint8, a: uint8):
    # Source-over blend of one RGBA pixel over the image, clipped.
    if a == 0:
        return
    if x < 0 or y < 0:
        return
    if x >= cast[int64](img_w) or y >= cast[int64](img_h):
        return
    o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](y) * img_w + cast[uint64](x)) * 4
    _vk2d_blend_at(o, r, g, b, a)


# --- rect fills ----------------------------------------------------

def vk2d_raster_fill_rect(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64, img_h: uint64,
                          x: int64, y: int64, w: int64, h: int64,
                          rgba: uint32):
    # Solid opaque fill of the rectangle (x,y,w,h) with rgba's RGB,
    # storing alpha 0xFF. Mirrors hamui_host _fill_rect / hamSDL
    # sdl_fill_rect (whose `fill` verb is opaque).
    if color_base == 0 or w <= 0 or h <= 0:
        return
    r: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 24) & 0xFF)
    g: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 16) & 0xFF)
    b: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 8) & 0xFF)
    if _vk2d_bgra != 0:
        rb_t: uint8 = r
        r = b
        b = rb_t
    # Hoist the clip to the whole rect: clamp to the image bounds ONCE,
    # then the inner loop is a bounds-check-free packed-word row store
    # (this is the fast CLEAR / opaque-fill path).
    iw: int64 = cast[int64](img_w)
    ih: int64 = cast[int64](img_h)
    x0: int64 = x
    y0: int64 = y
    x1: int64 = x + w
    y1: int64 = y + h
    if x0 < 0:
        x0 = 0
    if y0 < 0:
        y0 = 0
    if x1 > iw:
        x1 = iw
    if y1 > ih:
        y1 = ih
    if x0 >= x1 or y0 >= y1:
        return
    pword: uint32 = _vk2d_pack_opaque(r, g, b)
    yy: int64 = y0
    while yy < y1:
        o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](yy) * img_w
                                  + cast[uint64](x0)) * 4
        xx: int64 = x0
        while xx < x1:
            cast[Ptr[uint32]](o)[0] = pword
            o = o + 4
            xx = xx + 1
        yy = yy + 1


def vk2d_raster_fill_rect_alpha(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64,
                                img_h: uint64,
                                x: int64, y: int64, w: int64, h: int64,
                                rgba: uint32):
    # Source-over alpha fill: rgba's low byte is the source alpha. The
    # DE scrim/overlay and hamSDL translucent fills need this. Mirrors
    # hamui_host _fill_rect_a.
    if color_base == 0 or w <= 0 or h <= 0:
        return
    r: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 24) & 0xFF)
    g: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 16) & 0xFF)
    b: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 8) & 0xFF)
    a: uint8 = cast[uint8](rgba & 0xFF)
    if a == 0:
        return
    if _vk2d_bgra != 0:
        rb_t: uint8 = r
        r = b
        b = rb_t
    # Hoist the clip to the whole rect (clamp once, no per-pixel branch).
    iw: int64 = cast[int64](img_w)
    ih: int64 = cast[int64](img_h)
    x0: int64 = x
    y0: int64 = y
    x1: int64 = x + w
    y1: int64 = y + h
    if x0 < 0:
        x0 = 0
    if y0 < 0:
        y0 = 0
    if x1 > iw:
        x1 = iw
    if y1 > ih:
        y1 = ih
    if x0 >= x1 or y0 >= y1:
        return
    if a >= 255:
        # Fully opaque alpha fill == opaque store: packed-word fast path.
        pword: uint32 = _vk2d_pack_opaque(r, g, b)
        yy: int64 = y0
        while yy < y1:
            o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](yy) * img_w
                                      + cast[uint64](x0)) * 4
            xx: int64 = x0
            while xx < x1:
                cast[Ptr[uint32]](o)[0] = pword
                o = o + 4
                xx = xx + 1
            yy = yy + 1
        return
    # Translucent source-over fill: hoist the constant src*a terms out of
    # the inner loop; only the destination load varies per pixel.
    av: uint32 = cast[uint32](a)
    ia: uint32 = 255 - av
    rav: uint32 = cast[uint32](r) * av
    gav: uint32 = cast[uint32](g) * av
    bav: uint32 = cast[uint32](b) * av
    yr: int64 = y0
    while yr < y1:
        o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](yr) * img_w
                                  + cast[uint64](x0)) * 4
        xc: int64 = x0
        while xc < x1:
            dr: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0])
            dg: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0])
            db: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0])
            cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0] = cast[uint8]((rav + dr * ia) / 255)
            cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0] = cast[uint8]((gav + dg * ia) / 255)
            cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0] = cast[uint8]((bav + db * ia) / 255)
            cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 3)[0] = 255
            o = o + 4
            xc = xc + 1
        yr = yr + 1


# --- image / sprite / glyph-atlas blit -----------------------------

def vk2d_raster_blit(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64, img_h: uint64,
                     src_base: uint64, src_w: uint64, src_h: uint64,
                     dx: int64, dy: int64, dw: int64, dh: int64,
                     sx: int64, sy: int64, sw: int64, sh: int64):
    # Nearest-neighbour scaled, source-over-composited blit of a region
    # (sx,sy,sw,sh) of an RGBA8888 source image into the destination
    # rect (dx,dy,dw,dh). dw/dh<=0 -> use the source-rect size (natural,
    # unscaled). This is the primitive glyph/text, sprites, and window
    # scene images all sit on. Mirrors hamui_host _host_blit_image (and
    # is the target for hamSDL sdl_blit).
    if color_base == 0 or src_base == 0:
        return
    # Default the source rect to the whole source image.
    rsx: int64 = sx
    rsy: int64 = sy
    rsw: int64 = sw
    rsh: int64 = sh
    if rsw <= 0:
        rsw = cast[int64](src_w)
    if rsh <= 0:
        rsh = cast[int64](src_h)
    if rsx < 0:
        rsx = 0
    if rsy < 0:
        rsy = 0
    if rsx + rsw > cast[int64](src_w):
        rsw = cast[int64](src_w) - rsx
    if rsy + rsh > cast[int64](src_h):
        rsh = cast[int64](src_h) - rsy
    if rsw <= 0 or rsh <= 0:
        return
    tw: int64 = dw
    th: int64 = dh
    if tw <= 0:
        tw = rsw
    if th <= 0:
        th = rsh
    # Hoist the DESTINATION clip: restrict the yy/xx ranges to those whose
    # dest pixel (dx+xx, dy+yy) lands inside the image, so the inner loop
    # does no per-pixel bounds check. Skipped (clipped) pixels had no side
    # effect before, so the sampled/blended output is byte-identical.
    iw: int64 = cast[int64](img_w)
    ih: int64 = cast[int64](img_h)
    yy0: int64 = 0
    if dy < 0:
        yy0 = 0 - dy
    yy1: int64 = th
    if dy + th > ih:
        yy1 = ih - dy
    xx0: int64 = 0
    if dx < 0:
        xx0 = 0 - dx
    xx1: int64 = tw
    if dx + tw > iw:
        xx1 = iw - dx
    yy: int64 = yy0
    while yy < yy1:
        syi: int64 = rsy + (yy * rsh / th)
        if syi >= cast[int64](src_h):
            syi = cast[int64](src_h) - 1
        drow: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](dy + yy) * img_w
                                     + cast[uint64](dx + xx0)) * 4
        xx: int64 = xx0
        while xx < xx1:
            sxi: int64 = rsx + (xx * rsw / tw)
            if sxi >= cast[int64](src_w):
                sxi = cast[int64](src_w) - 1
            soff: uint64 = src_base + (cast[uint64](syi) * src_w
                                       + cast[uint64](sxi)) * 4
            sr: uint8 = cast[Ptr[uint8]](soff)[0]
            sg: uint8 = cast[Ptr[uint8]](soff + 1)[0]
            sb: uint8 = cast[Ptr[uint8]](soff + 2)[0]
            sa: uint8 = cast[Ptr[uint8]](soff + 3)[0]
            if _vk2d_bgra != 0:
                # Source stays RGBA; flip R/B so the BGRA destination gets
                # the correct visible color (byte0=B, byte2=R).
                srb_t: uint8 = sr
                sr = sb
                sb = srb_t
            _vk2d_blend_at(drow, sr, sg, sb, sa)
            drow = drow + 4
            xx = xx + 1
        yy = yy + 1


# --- coverage-mask blit (glyph / anti-aliased ink) -----------------
#
# Phase B (hamSDL) needs to paint anti-aliased TEXT: each glyph is a small
# W*H COVERAGE bitmap (one alpha byte per pixel, 0..255) produced by the font
# rasterizer (lib/font_ttf.ad), stamped in ONE solid ink colour. This is the
# "glyph coverage-mask op" Phase A anticipated — the missing 2D primitive that
# let the font stack stay caller-side. It is also the exact per-pixel-coverage
# path a rounded-rect AA corner or any AA mask needs.
#
# cov_base points at a row-major, cov_w*cov_h array of uint8 coverage. The ink
# colour's own alpha (rgba low byte) MODULATES the coverage, so a translucent
# ink over a partial-coverage edge composites correctly:
#     a_eff = cov * (rgba & 0xFF) / 255 ; then source-over blend the RGB.
# cov==0 leaves the destination untouched. With an opaque ink (alpha 0xFF)
# a_eff == cov, byte-identical to hamui_host _blit_glyph_prop's per-pixel
# _put_px_blend(x, y, r, g, b, cov) — so a host glyph blitted through this op
# reproduces the compositor's anti-aliased text exactly.

def vk2d_raster_cov_mask(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64, img_h: uint64,
                         cov_base: uint64, cov_w: int64, cov_h: int64,
                         dx: int64, dy: int64, rgba: uint32):
    if color_base == 0 or cov_base == 0 or cov_w <= 0 or cov_h <= 0:
        return
    r: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 24) & 0xFF)
    g: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 16) & 0xFF)
    b: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 8) & 0xFF)
    ca: uint32 = rgba & 0xFF
    if ca == 0:
        return
    if _vk2d_bgra != 0:
        rb_t: uint8 = r
        r = b
        b = rb_t
    # Hoist the destination clip: restrict row/col to the coverage cells
    # whose dest pixel is in-image, so the per-pixel path has no bounds
    # branch.
    iw: int64 = cast[int64](img_w)
    ih: int64 = cast[int64](img_h)
    row0: int64 = 0
    if dy < 0:
        row0 = 0 - dy
    row1: int64 = cov_h
    if dy + cov_h > ih:
        row1 = ih - dy
    col0: int64 = 0
    if dx < 0:
        col0 = 0 - dx
    col1: int64 = cov_w
    if dx + cov_w > iw:
        col1 = iw - dx
    if ca >= 255:
        # OPAQUE ink fast path (the overwhelmingly common text/AA-ink case):
        # the ink alpha is 255, so a_eff == cov*255/255 == cov exactly and the
        # per-pixel composite collapses to the CANONICAL branch-free coverage
        # blend the SSE2 auto-vectorizer (codegen.ad try_vectorize_glyph)
        # matches — 12 statements, no cov==0 skip, alpha forced 255:
        #     ia = 255 - cov ; out = (chan*cov + dst*(255-cov)) / 255.
        # This is byte-identical to _vk2d_blend_at(a=cov): cov==255 -> chan
        # (opaque store), cov==0 -> dst unchanged (the alpha byte the skip
        # used to leave is written 255, same value the composite target holds),
        # 0<cov<255 -> the same integer blend. Under --opt the inner loop is
        # replaced by a 4-px/iter SSE2 preamble + this scalar remainder drain;
        # with --opt OFF this scalar loop ships unchanged.
        r32: uint32 = cast[uint32](r)
        g32: uint32 = cast[uint32](g)
        b32: uint32 = cast[uint32](b)
        yrow: int64 = row0
        while yrow < row1:
            coff: uint64 = cov_base + cast[uint64](yrow * cov_w + col0)
            o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](dy + yrow) * img_w
                                      + cast[uint64](dx + col0)) * 4
            col: int64 = col0
            while col < col1:
                cov: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](coff)[0])
                ia: uint32 = 255 - cov
                dr: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0])
                dg: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0])
                db: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0])
                cast[Ptr[uint8]](o)[0] = cast[uint8]((r32 * cov + dr * ia) / 255)
                cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 1)[0] = cast[uint8]((g32 * cov + dg * ia) / 255)
                cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 2)[0] = cast[uint8]((b32 * cov + db * ia) / 255)
                cast[Ptr[uint8]](o + 3)[0] = 255
                o = o + 4
                coff = coff + 1
                col = col + 1
            yrow = yrow + 1
        return
    # TRANSLUCENT ink (ca < 255): the coverage is modulated by the ink alpha
    # (a_eff = cov*ca/255), which the canonical glyph form cannot express, so
    # keep the exact per-pixel scalar path with the cov==0 skip. Uncommon.
    row: int64 = row0
    while row < row1:
        coff: uint64 = cov_base + cast[uint64](row * cov_w + col0)
        o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](dy + row) * img_w
                                  + cast[uint64](dx + col0)) * 4
        col: int64 = col0
        while col < col1:
            cov: uint32 = cast[uint32](cast[Ptr[uint8]](coff)[0])
            if cov != 0:
                a_eff: uint32 = cov * ca / 255
                _vk2d_blend_at(o, r, g, b, cast[uint8](a_eff))
            coff = coff + 1
            o = o + 4
            col = col + 1
        row = row + 1


# --- rounded-rect fill (anti-aliased corners) ----------------------
#
# The modern (KDE-ish) button/card/tile primitive hamSDL's sdl_fill_round_rect
# and the DE both draw. Ported BYTE-FOR-BYTE from hamui_host _fill_roundrect /
# _rr_cov / _rr_isqrt (whose twin is the kernel compositor _wsys_* rounder), so
# a rounded rect routed through vk reproduces the exact same AA corner pixels.
# `corners` is a bitmask (1=TL 2=TR 4=BL 8=BR; 15=all); rgba low byte = alpha.

def _vk2d_rr_isqrt(n: uint64) -> uint64:
    # floor(sqrt(n)) via integer Newton iteration (compositor-identical).
    if n == 0:
        return 0
    x: uint64 = n
    y: uint64 = (x + 1) / 2
    while y < x:
        x = y
        y = (x + n / x) / 2
    return x


def _vk2d_rr_cov(px: int64, py: int64, ccx2: int64, ccy2: int64,
                 r2: int64) -> int32:
    # Corner coverage 0..255 for pixel (px,py) against an arc centred at
    # (ccx2,ccy2) radius r2, all in HALF-pixel (2x) integer units.
    dxh: int64 = (2 * px + 1) - ccx2
    dyh: int64 = (2 * py + 1) - ccy2
    d2: int64 = dxh * dxh + dyh * dyh
    dh: int64 = cast[int64](_vk2d_rr_isqrt(cast[uint64](d2)))
    if dh <= r2 - 1:
        return 255
    if dh >= r2 + 1:
        return 0
    return cast[int32]((r2 + 1 - dh) * 255 / 2)


def vk2d_raster_fill_roundrect(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64,
                               img_h: uint64,
                               x: int64, y: int64, w: int64, h: int64,
                               rad: int64, corners: int32, rgba: uint32):
    if color_base == 0 or w <= 0 or h <= 0:
        return
    r: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 24) & 0xFF)
    g: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 16) & 0xFF)
    b: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 8) & 0xFF)
    a: uint32 = rgba & 0xFF
    if a == 0:
        return
    rr: int64 = rad
    if rr < 0:
        rr = 0
    if rr > w / 2:
        rr = w / 2
    if rr > h / 2:
        rr = h / 2
    if rr <= 0:
        # No rounding: a plain source-over rectangle. Delegate with the
        # ORIGINAL rgba — fill_rect_alpha applies the BGRA swap itself, so
        # we must not pre-swap here (that would double-swap).
        vk2d_raster_fill_rect_alpha(color_base, img_w, img_h, x, y, w, h, rgba)
        return
    # Rounded path draws through _vk2d_blend_at directly, so apply the BGRA
    # R/B swap to our own ink locals (byte0=B, byte2=R on the store).
    if _vk2d_bgra != 0:
        rb_t: uint8 = r
        r = b
        b = rb_t
    r2: int64 = 2 * rr
    tlx2: int64 = 2 * (x + rr)
    tly2: int64 = 2 * (y + rr)
    trx2: int64 = 2 * (x + w - rr)
    try2: int64 = tly2
    blx2: int64 = tlx2
    bly2: int64 = 2 * (y + h - rr)
    brx2: int64 = trx2
    bry2: int64 = bly2
    # Hoist the clip: clamp the py/px sweep to the image bounds once. The
    # corner-coverage classification uses absolute px/py, so clamping the
    # loop range only drops pixels that were clipped anyway — byte-exact.
    iw: int64 = cast[int64](img_w)
    ih: int64 = cast[int64](img_h)
    px0: int64 = x
    if px0 < 0:
        px0 = 0
    px1: int64 = x + w
    if px1 > iw:
        px1 = iw
    py0: int64 = y
    if py0 < 0:
        py0 = 0
    py1: int64 = y + h
    if py1 > ih:
        py1 = ih
    if px0 >= px1 or py0 >= py1:
        return
    py: int64 = py0
    while py < py1:
        in_top: int32 = 0
        if py < y + rr:
            in_top = 1
        in_bot: int32 = 0
        if py >= y + h - rr:
            in_bot = 1
        o: uint64 = color_base + (cast[uint64](py) * img_w
                                  + cast[uint64](px0)) * 4
        px: int64 = px0
        while px < px1:
            cov: int32 = 255
            in_left: int32 = 0
            if px < x + rr:
                in_left = 1
            in_right: int32 = 0
            if px >= x + w - rr:
                in_right = 1
            if in_top == 1 and in_left == 1 and (corners & 1) != 0:
                cov = _vk2d_rr_cov(px, py, tlx2, tly2, r2)
            elif in_top == 1 and in_right == 1 and (corners & 2) != 0:
                cov = _vk2d_rr_cov(px, py, trx2, try2, r2)
            elif in_bot == 1 and in_left == 1 and (corners & 4) != 0:
                cov = _vk2d_rr_cov(px, py, blx2, bly2, r2)
            elif in_bot == 1 and in_right == 1 and (corners & 8) != 0:
                cov = _vk2d_rr_cov(px, py, brx2, bry2, r2)
            if cov > 0:
                ae: uint32 = a * cast[uint32](cov) / 255
                _vk2d_blend_at(o, r, g, b, cast[uint8](ae))
            o = o + 4
            px = px + 1
        py = py + 1


# --- line ----------------------------------------------------------

def vk2d_raster_draw_line(color_base: uint64, img_w: uint64, img_h: uint64,
                          x1: int64, y1: int64, x2: int64, y2: int64,
                          thick: int64, rgba: uint32):
    # Opaque Bresenham line with a thick x thick square brush per plotted
    # point — byte-identical brush model to hamui_host _draw_line and
    # hamSDL sdl_draw_line_t.
    if color_base == 0:
        return
    r: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 24) & 0xFF)
    g: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 16) & 0xFF)
    b: uint8 = cast[uint8]((rgba >> 8) & 0xFF)
    if _vk2d_bgra != 0:
        rb_t: uint8 = r
        r = b
        b = rb_t
    dx: int64 = x2 - x1
    if dx < 0:
        dx = 0 - dx
    dy: int64 = y2 - y1
    if dy < 0:
        dy = 0 - dy
    sx: int64 = 1
    if x1 > x2:
        sx = -1
    sy: int64 = 1
    if y1 > y2:
        sy = -1
    err: int64 = dx - dy
    cx: int64 = x1
    cy: int64 = y1
    t: int64 = thick
    if t < 1:
        t = 1
    guard: int64 = 0
    while guard < 100000:
        # square brush: t*t opaque pixels at (cx,cy)
        by: int64 = 0
        while by < t:
            bx: int64 = 0
            while bx < t:
                _vk2d_store(color_base, img_w, img_h, cx + bx, cy + by,
                            r, g, b, 255)
                bx = bx + 1
            by = by + 1
        if cx == x2 and cy == y2:
            return
        e2: int64 = err * 2
        if e2 > (0 - dy):
            err = err - dy
            cx = cx + sx
        if e2 < dx:
            err = err + dx
            cy = cy + sy
        guard = guard + 1
